n his book and exposes the anxieties caused by such seemingly pornographic work as the infamous Made in Heaven series. Featuring cameos by other leading artists, including Liam Gillick, Jenny Holzer, Karen Kilimnik, and Tino Sehgal, the drama Bunzl narrates is palpable and entertaining and sheds an altogether new light on the contemporary art boom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aArt museumsxCuratorshipzIllinoiszChicago. 0aArt museumszIllinoiszChicago. 0aArt, ModernvExhibitions. 0aArt, ModernxExhibitions. 0aKoons, Jeff, -- 1955- -- Museums.;Museum of Contemporary Art (Chicago, Ill.);Art, Modern -- Exhibitions.;Art museums -- Illinois -- Chicago.;Museums -- Curatorship -- Illinois -- Chicago. 0aMuseumsxCuratorshipzIllinoiszChicago. 7aART / General.2bisacsh  aanthropology, contemporary art, museum, avant-garde, chicago, cultural institutions, culture studies, liam gillick, jenny holzer, karen kilimnik, tino sehgal, exhibitions, curators, public awareness, ethnography, neoliberal america, united states, usa, insightful, unusual, experimental, aesthetic innovation, initial unacceptability, pushing boundaries, reform, social commentary.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226173955423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226173955/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles